name: Only 2 stops to Manhattan studio
description: Comfortable studio apartment with super comfortable king size bed and  full kitchen and bathroom located in FABULOUS Williamsburg, Brooklyn.
host_about:
We love to travel. When we travel we like to stay in a comfortable place that is clean, neat and sweet smelling, for a reasonable price. That's what we rent to you. We love city life but we also love outdoor adventures. We like keep up with all that's new and exciting around New York and we're happy to tell you where to find it. Want to hear the new young musicians that people are excited about or the promising new artists - we'll tell you about them. The best restaurants - ask us.
Want to take a break from the city we'll tell you about wilderness canoeing on the Delaware river - just an hour and a half's drive. We can tell you where to find the great salt water fishing with clean beautiful waters just an hour away from the city or how to take a one day trip by bus to ski in Vermont.


WHY WILLIAMSBURG?

Williamsburg is FABULOUS. It's fast growing and it's fast changing. It's hip. In the 1960's the new and exciting place where culture was blooming was Greenwich Village. In the 70's the SOHO neighborhood was where cheap industrial loft space were being turned into places where the adventurous could move to New York, live cheaply and make the new art, music, and culture. These days Williamsburg has that special chemistry of the New York that's constantly renewing itself.

name: Spacious fully furnished 2 BR near Central Park
description: Experience a charming apartment in the heart of the Upper East Side on East 94th Street between 1st - 2nd Avenue (walk-up building) Perfect for couples, solo adventurers, business travelers, and families. Just steps from the Q subway station, Central Park, and the Guggenheim Museum. Discover designer stores and immerse yourself in the vibrant neighborhood. Book now and embrace the allure of the Upper East Side's prime location
neighborhood_overview:
Discover the vibrant neighborhood of the Upper East Side, where convenience and excitement converge. Located on East 94th Street between 1st and 2nd Avenue, this area offers a wealth of highlights just steps away from the apartment.

Immerse yourself in a shopper's paradise, as the neighborhood is home to renowned designer stores, giving you access to the latest fashion trends. Indulge in a culinary journey at well-known restaurants, or enjoy a night out at the nearby cinemas, comedy clubs, and coffee shops. For a quick caffeine fix, there's a Starbucks coffee shop conveniently located across the street from the building.

Nature enthusiasts will delight in the proximity to Central Park, the Metropolitan Museum, and the Guggenheim Museum, offering a wealth of cultural experiences and breathtaking landscapes.

Convenience is key in this neighborhood, with an array of amenities just minutes from the apartment. You'll find drug stores, nail salons, a US Post
host_about:
The Local Stay, founded in 2008 and offers hundreds of short-term and long-term rental properties in Amsterdam, Barcelona, Buenos Aires, London, New York, New-Jersey, Paris, Rome, Tel Aviv and more. Our apartments inventory includes both corporate apartments and privately owned flats, making The Local Stay the perfect option for business travelers, corporate relocation clients and those on sabbatical, as well as foreign students.
The Local Stay makes the process of renting furnished short- and long-term apartments absolutely transparent, so renters and property owners alike can rest easy.
At The Local Stay, our goal is to take the guess work out of it, carefully curating apartments so that travelers experience the true pulse of the city. And, since each property owner is personally vetted by The Local Stay team, travelers can rest assured that their stays will be safe and secure. Better vetting means that travelers get the most exclusive apartments in the most central locations, while greater involvement by The Local Stay means that property owners can list it and leave it as we handle communication with renters
With options for everyone, The Local Stay provides personalized service so that every traveler can stay like a local.

name: 2 bedroom Williamsburg Apt - Bedford L stop
description: I love my apartment and I love being able to offer it to visitors. I know traveling is fun but also exhausting and I hope my house makes your trip a little easier and more personal feeling than some boxy hotel room. My apartment is sunny and bright and big, with high tin ceilings and loads of charm. It's near three different subway lines, is one stop from Manhattan and also the Wililamsburg Bridge is a few blocks away if you feel like taking a nice walk. There's also the ferry. So many options!
neighborhood_overview: Williamsburg has been Williamsburg for a long time but it's just exploding right now! So many new shops and restaurants opening. There seems to be a new place to eat every week. Across the street from my apartment is a movie theater. If you're hungry, there's a Japanese restaurant, a Korean bbq place and a ramen place on just that ONE block. It's just a great neighborhood. Filled with hipsters for sure but so much more too.
host_about: I'm a writer.  I do a lot of stories for the public radio show "This American Life."  I'm working on a book which is why I am away from my place.  I'm not crazy or passive aggressive.  I am also not all that tall.  I love my apartment and would love to have non crazy people staying in it who will also love it.

There are restaurants, bars, high end retail chain stores and local entrepreneur shops. Our neighborhood is safe day and night with people out at all hours on the subways and streets.

We hope you have checked out one of the many stories written about our home online and we welcome the opportunity to share it with you. 

A little about us and the home ...

David is a seasoned New Yorker with roots on the lower east side and has lived in this area of Brooklyn for about 20 years. Janet is more recently relocated to Brooklyn from Philadelphia, though roots with David go back to childhood days. We are newlyweds as of July 11, 2015

The building received its C of O in 2013 after many challenges from NYC's department of buildings. You can read or listen to the story online. We are Brooklyn's and NYC's first shipping container home. NPR Science Friday has a lovely interview with David and late wife and architect, Michele Bertomen.

We like to leave people alone unless they need us. But we are around all the time and live on the second and third floor. Our Giant dog, Mormon, is very gentle and a fully trained therapy dog.  If you have any concerns about dogs, I will refer you to our reviews. 

We hope that we can offer a comfortable, safe home away from home in the heart of trendy Brooklyn.

Covid-19 Vaccination is a requirement for booking with us. 

David and Janet

description: This spacious, bright, and modern loft is located in a quiet tree lined street in the heart of trendy East Williamsburg. It is ideal for travelers seeking a true NY Experience. Perfectly located just 3 blocks away from the Graham L Train.
neighborhood_overview:
Just 3 blocks away from the Graham “L” train and steps away from numerous gourmet restaurants, bars and shops, this apartment is only 8 minutes and 3 stops away from the East Village in Manhattan. The location could not be more perfect.


Just 1 block away you have delicious restaurants like Cozy Royale, Mesa Coyoacan, Good Thanks and Hummus Market.
Enjoy the amazing tacos and live music at Union Pool, just 3 blocks away! Are you a pizza lover? Roberta's one of NY's finest pizza places is only 10 minutes walk away, a must in Brooklyn.
The McCarren park is also a nice area to have a quiet Brooklyn afternoon or go to Williamsburg Water front and watch the sunset from the piers.
host_about:
Hello Everyone!!!

I am a young entrepreneur living the life between Williamsburg, Brooklyn and Woodstock, NY. I own 2 retail gift shops in New York called Casa Ziki. I love to travel and eat delicious food. I have a strong passion for design, fashion, art, and music. 

If you stay at my loft I promise you will want to come back :) it is full of great energy and vibes.

Location Location Location! 73rd Street & 3rd Avenue in MANHATTAN

description: Cozy, one bedroom apartment all to yourself in Williamsburg, Brooklyn. One stop from Manhattan's Lower East Side on the JMZ train! Perfect location for exploring Brooklyn or Manhattan. Fast WIFI. Linens and basic toiletries provided. Guests are free to rearrange furniture to suit their needs :)
neighborhood_overview: Williamsburg, Brooklyn is an amazing neighborhood! It offers a mix of traditional and trendy cafes, diverse range of restaurants, music venues, shops and art galleries. Accessiblity to fresh fruits and vegetables at reasonable prices is one of my favorite things about the area! Truly unique for NYC.
host_about:

I hope that my guests feel as comfortable in my apartment as in their own home.

The apt is an ideal location for exploring Brooklyn and NYC, as it is close to citi bikes, the subway and a bus terminal.

The neighborhood and my building are very safe.

name: Your Very Own Williamsburg Apt!
description:
This is an ENTIRE apt to yourself in the artsy, bar and food hub of Williamsburg, Brooklyn! The apt is located on a very QUIET street in a SAFE neighborhood. Great restaurants, shopping and public transport are within a short walking distance. It's a wonderful place to call home while staying in New York!

5 min walk to the Graham L stop
15 min walk to BEDFORD AVE
25 min to UNION SQUARE
40 min to MIDTOWN
Plenty of street parking
Loads of restaurants and shopping

30 night min and above
neighborhood_overview:
What do I NOT love about this neighborhood?! This is the perfect place to live and to visit if you are planning a trip to New York. The apartment is set on a quiet and safe street. Directly around the corner, go to the "Tar Pit" for a delicious coffee, or head the other direction and grab a piece of pie at "The Blue Stove". Check out all the great artisan stores on Graham avenue, right next to the Italian specialty shops that have been around for decades. Visit Graham Ave Meats for "The Godfather" sandwich. Consistently voted #1 sandwich in all of NYC!
The "L" train is only a 5 minute walk, and 3 stops will get you into Manhattan. Walk 10 minutes to Bedford Avenue, which is known for its nightlife and shopping. Have a weekend brunch and enjoy all the people- watching! Walk down to the waters edge and see the ultimate view of Manhattan (you'll remember it is an island!). The apartment is also right on the border of Greenpoint, and McCarren Park. Walk to McCarren park and swim in
host_about: Experienced traveler and long time host. Always treat my treat my stays as if it were my own home.

With convenient proximity to the subway and easy access to public transportation, tenants will be able to make the most out of their time in New York.

- Prime Manhattan location, near subway station and bus stops
- On-site management office
- Multilingual management team 
- Key-less electronic entry system allows for effortless, 24-hour check-in

name: Williamsburg Condo w/ Backyard
description: Our light-filled,  two-level condo is the perfect place to stay to enjoy Williamsburg, Brooklyn and Manhattan. We are located 1 subway stop from Manhattan - a 7 minute walk to the Bedford L stop and a 5 minute walk to the Marcy Avenue J M Z stops. Williamsburg is full of shops, restaurants and home to a beautiful riverfront park - Domino Park.
neighborhood_overview:
Williamburg is safe, convenient and quite a poplular destination for foodies, as there are a plethora of popular bars and restaurants. There are 3 fabulous restaurants on the same block of this apartment and so many more within a 5-10 minute walk.

Neighborhood music venues include Williamsburg Music Hall, the Knitting Factory, Glasslands, Brooklyn Bowl; Nitehawk, an awesome indie dinner movie theater is close by, so is Williamsburg Cinemas. A neighborhood waterfront park is 3 blocks away, the nearest Citibike rental station is 2 blocks away, and you're a 12-minute walk away from the East River Ferry terminal, where you can catch a fun boat ride to Dumbo, Lower Manhattan and Governor's Island. And you can even walk over the Williamsburg bridge to Manhattan in about 1/2 hr.

description: This Newly renovated 2 Bedroom 1 Bath is the perfect base of operations during your time in NYC. Equipped with everything you need to make you stay convenient and comfortable. The unit has been designed to be convenient and luxurious, with high end furniture and beautiful artwork. Located in the safe and charming UES, enjoy all that city has to offer and more!
neighborhood_overview:
The Upper East Side (UES), located in Manhattan, New York City, is a prestigious neighborhood known for its elegance, sophistication, and affluent residents. Bounded by 96th Street to the north, the East River to the east, 59th Street to the south, and Central Park and Fifth Avenue to the west, it’s home to several smaller neighborhoods, including Lenox Hill, Carnegie Hill, and Yorkville.

The UES is renowned for its luxurious townhouses, upscale apartment buildings, and iconic Park Avenue. It offers a slower, more relaxed pace compared to other neighborhoods in the city. The area is also known for its prominent cultural institutions, unparalleled shopping, distinguished prep schools, and immaculate landscaping.

Residents can enjoy playtime in Central Park, access to numerous cultural institutions, and a vibrant nightlife. The UES truly offers a sprawling, self-contained Manhattan retreat.

description:
Studio apartment in Astoria. Comfortable and sunny, very clean and spacious.
Two blocks from subway station and 15 min from Manhattan. Newly renovated. The apartment fits a single person or couple.
neighborhood_overview:
Places of interest[edit]
Attractions in Astoria include the Kaufman Astoria Studios' Museum of the Moving Image, Isamu Noguchi Museum, and Socrates Sculpture Park. Astoria Park, along the East River, is Astoria's largest park and also contains the largest of New York City's public pools (at 330 feet long)[24] which was also the former site of the 1936 and 1964 U.S. Olympic trials.
The Hell Gate Bridge and New York Connecting Railroad viaduct rise high above Astoria.
The oldest beer garden in New York City, Bohemian Hall, was founded in 1910 when Astoria was largely Irish, Italian, Bohemian (Czech), and Slovak.[25]
The Greater Astoria Historical Society in the historic Quinn Memorial Building on the corner of Broadway and 36th Street serves as a valuable historical resource as well as providing tourist information.
St. Michael's Cemetery on Astoria Boulevard is the burial place of composer and pianist Scott Joplin.[26] and gangster Frank Costello.
Steinway

host_about:
I work in Documentary Film & TV but dabble in other creative media like music and photography…here’s a bit about me...

Peter is a film & television director, producer, and EP with sixteen years of international experience creating documentary feature films, docuseries, hosted unscripted television, and branded content working with Netflix, HBO, CBS, ABC, Discovery Channel, National Geographic, History, CNN, USA, Travel Channel and brands such as Redbull, AirBnB, Toyota, GMC, Polaris, Jeep, Reef, Roxy, and Quiksilver. 

Peter’s innate love for adventure is palpable. The California native and UC Berkeley alum started his career working on Survivor, traveling to the most remote corners of the globe as the youngest producer of the groundbreaking series. Since then, Peter's work includes the supervision, development, production, and delivery of a vast range of subjects (Website hidden by Airbnb) After traveling to over 90 countries, Peter is fluent in Spanish and Portuguese. He is committed to developing and producing compelling content with a purpose. Peter believes that storytellers have a distinct responsibility to bring entertaining, authentic stories to the screen.

***** ABOUT THE NEIGHBORHOOD:

Yorksville used to be known as Hungarian town. Now it is home to a diverse mix of foreign cultures, but still holds a friendly neighbourhood feel, which you can experience at any of the following joints:

* German restaurant and deli with imported Heidelberg on Second Ave between 85th and 86th

*Hungarian bakery and candy Orwhashes on 78th between 1 and 2 Ave

*Andre's Hungarian bakery and pastry and pizza on Second Ave between 84th and 85th

*Hot dogs and frankfurters in Papaya on the corner of 3 Ave with 86th

* Orwashers on 78th st., Best bread in NY, period!

***** OTHER RESTAURANTS:

*Hunan Delight chinese restaurant on the corner of 78th and York
Great for lunch! Very good price!

*Melon Burgers on the corner of Third Avenue and 79th
Yummmy!

*Gino's Italian restaurant on 83th between 1 and 2 Ave
My parents love this restaurant!

AFI REALTY and PROPERTY MANAGEMENT | Corporate Furnished Apartments 

**30 Days Minimum and UP**


AFI Property Management provides high-end furnished and serviced apartments for rent on the Upper East Side of New York. host_about:
The Local Stay, founded in 2008 and offers hundreds of short-term and long-term rental properties in Amsterdam, Barcelona, Buenos Aires, London, New York, New-Jersey, Paris, Rome, Tel Aviv and more. Our apartments inventory includes both corporate apartments and privately owned flats, making The Local Stay the perfect option for business travelers, corporate relocation clients and those on sabbatical, as well as foreign students.
The Local Stay makes the process of renting furnished short- and long-term apartments absolutely transparent, so renters and property owners alike can rest easy.
At The Local Stay, our goal is to take the guess work out of it, carefully curating apartments so that travelers experience the true pulse of the city. And, since each property owner is personally vetted by The Local Stay team, travelers can rest assured that their stays will be safe and secure. neighborhood_overview:
To many New Yorkers, the Upper East Side connotes old money and high society. Alongside Central Park, between 5th and Lexington avenues, up to East 96th Street, the trappings of wealth are everywhere apparent: posh buildings, Madison Avenue's flagship boutiques, and doormen in braided livery. It’s also a key destination for visitors, because some of the most fantastic museums in the country are here.

There's a reason this stretch of Manhattan is called "Museum Mile": this is where you'll find the Metropolitan Museum of Art, the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum, the Cooper Hewitt, Smithsonian Design Museum, as well as a number of art galleries. For a local taste of the luxe life, catwalk down Madison Avenue for its lavish boutiques; strolling the platinum-card corridor between 60th and 82nd street is like stepping into the pages of a glossy magazine. Many fashion houses have their flagships here and showcase their lush threads in exquisite settings.

neighborhood_overview:
To many New Yorkers, the Upper East Side connotes old money and high society. Alongside Central Park, between 5th and Lexington avenues, up to East 96th Street, the trappings of wealth are everywhere apparent: posh buildings, Madison Avenue's flagship boutiques, and doormen in braided livery. It’s also a key destination for visitors, because some of the most fantastic museums in the country are here.

There's a reason this stretch of Manhattan is called "Museum Mile": this is where you'll find the Metropolitan Museum of Art, the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum, the Cooper Hewitt, Smithsonian Design Museum, as well as a number of art galleries. For a local taste of the luxe life, catwalk down Madison Avenue for its lavish boutiques; strolling the platinum-card corridor between 60th and 82nd street is like stepping into the pages of a glossy magazine. Many fashion houses have their flagships here and showcase their lush threads in exquisite settings.

neighborhood_overview:
Yorkville is on the Upper East Side in Manhattan. Its commercial hub is along 86th Street. For designer boutiques and other high-end shops and restaurants, residents head to Second and Third Avenues. The area’s many leafy side streets lead to tiny parks and open spaces, including John Jay Playground, which offers two public outdoor pools, and basketball and tennis courts. Asphalt Green, the sprawling athletic center, is nearby with its Olympic-size swimming pool, soccer and basketball fields, and other recreational amenities. The East River Esplanade is a popular spot for joggers, dog owners, and bicyclists. Yorkville is also home to public pools that overlook the East River. There is a footbridge to Randall’s Island with its vast green spaces and cultural outdoor events in the summer, where the Frieze New York Art Show takes place each spring.

The epicenter of haute hipster culture, Williamsburg features fine dining, casual dining, nightlife, shopping, art, recreation, and music. Meanwhile, Manhattan's ultra trendy Lower East Side neighborhood is just across the river. While it seems that everyone has an opinion on Williamsburg’s true cultural cache, those that live in the neighborhood prefer not to overthink it. Instead, you’ll find a refreshingly care-free community where the motto is “do your own thing” - and always have a good time along the way. Welcome to Williamsburg - Brooklyn - New York, friend! S 8th Street between Wythe & Bedford: This is a safe, peaceful neighborhood that is ideal for quiet travelers and tourists. Complete with neighborhood watch and stringent weekend noise restrictions. We ask guests to please be respectful of our neighbors

The Hou
host_about: In 1998, my husband & I purchased our circa 1871 Brownstone on East 62nd Street on the Upper East Side and began the process of "fixing" the house while being careful not to obliterate its history. We've managed the house for 28 years (& counting!) & enjoy meeting and getting to know all our guests.

neighborhood_overview:
The Upper East Side of Manhattan is the most elegant neighbor, with mostly one family homes. Very limited commercial traffic makes it charming and quite.
Central Park is a short walk away and highly recommended for a walk, a bike ride or a boat ride on the lake. The stretch of Fifth Avenue next door is known as “The Museum Mile” for the so many great museums New York has to offer: The Metropolitan, The Guggenheim, The Frick, the Cooper Hewitt and many more.

neighborhood_overview:

The apartment is on a quiet block off of Bedford Avenue, which is the main street in the neighborhood. It is 3 blocks away from the waterfront Domino Park. There is easy access to subways, buses, electric scooters, and citibikes. It's such a great neighborhood, our guests never want to leave!

description: Charming, stylish and fully furnished studio apartment with all necessary amenities.
neighborhood_overview:
To many New Yorkers, the Upper East Side connotes old money and high society. Alongside Central Park, between 5th and Lexington avenues, up to East 96th Street, the trappings of wealth are everywhere apparent: posh buildings, Madison Avenue's flagship boutiques, and doormen in braided livery. It’s also a key destination for visitors, because some of the most fantastic museums in the country are here.

There's a reason this stretch of Manhattan is called "Museum Mile": this is where you'll find the Metropolitan Museum of Art, the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum, the Cooper Hewitt, Smithsonian Design Museum, as well as a number of art galleries. For a local taste of the luxe life, catwalk down Madison Avenue for its lavish boutiques; strolling the platinum-card corridor between 60th and 82nd street is like stepping into the pages of a glossy magazine. Many fashion houses have their flagships here and showcase their lush threads in exquisite settings.

neighborhood_overview:
Williamsburg has exploded in recent years to become the defining cultural force of New York City. From its industrial past, the neighborhood underwent a hipster-centric renaissance that is still evidenced in the plethora of indie music performances, gallery shows, local artisan storefronts and pop-ups. The area is also home to a number distilleries and wineries that show off the neighborhood’s flair for locally made spirits, while Smorgasburg packs in creative food vendors along the riverfront on summer Saturdays. Williamsburg is one of the City’s most exciting nightlife neighborhoods too, with many of NYC’s trendiest restaurants and clubs.

Because of its storied past, the neighborhood is home to diverse mix of longtime Brooklyn pioneers and creative newcomers, a true reflection of the multicultural mixing pot that is New York City. Central Williamsburg is still mostly walk-up apartments and row homes while luxury high-rises and condos have shoot up all over the waterfront

neighborhood_overview:
Williamsburg has exploded in recent years to become the defining cultural force of New York City. From its industrial past, the neighborhood underwent a hipster-centric renaissance that is still evidenced in the plethora of indie music performances, gallery shows, local artisan storefronts and pop-ups. The area is also home to a number distilleries and wineries that show off the neighborhood’s flair for locally made spirits, while Smorgasburg packs in creative food vendors along the riverfront on summer Saturdays. Williamsburg is one of the City’s most exciting nightlife neighborhoods too, with many of NYC’s trendiest restaurants and clubs.

Because of its storied past, the neighborhood is home to diverse mix of longtime Brooklyn pioneers and creative newcomers, a true reflection of the multicultural mixing pot that is New York City. Central Williamsburg is still mostly walk-up apartments and row homes while luxury high-rises and condos have shoot up all over the waterfront

host_about:
Hi, I'm Arlene!
I'm a dentist living and practicing in Rochester, NY.  We were born and raised in Brooklyn, NY.
This airbnb listing is our home-away-from-home. My entire family and two daughters live in the NY/NJ area.
We love the city and come down when we are able.

My husband, is a musician, former teacher and our dental office manager. He loves table tennis and is in a league here in Rochester.

We love to travel, anywhere and everywhere! We have been to Europe, South America, Japan and of course our beautiful country as well.
Visiting museums, art galleries, historical sites and just meandering around is what we love. Best of all though is food and drink! Experiencing the cuisine of each country is so much fun to do.

Aside from travel and family we enjoy reading, binging on Netflix and walking the parks in this beautiful part of the state. Hey, come visit us up here near the Finger Lakes!

We love meeting people from different parts of the world and I look forward connecting with you as a host or traveler.

I will do my best to make your stay as comfortable and enjoyable as possible!!

neighborhood_overview:
The Upper East Side is one of the most affluent neighborhoods in New York City, known for its luxury high-rise buildings, exclusive shops, and prestigious cultural institutions. The location of this apartment on 75th Street and 2nd-3rd Avenue puts it in the heart of this neighborhood.

The area is home to many famous museums, such as the Metropolitan Museum of Art and the Guggenheim, as well as other cultural institutions like the Whitney Museum of American Art. The neighborhood is also home to many high-end shops and designer boutiques, such as Louis Vuitton, Gucci, and Chanel.

The area also boasts many excellent restaurants, cafes, and bars, catering to a variety of tastes and budgets. Some of the most popular include Cafe Boulud, Sushi Nakazawa, and the Carlyle Hotel's Bemelmans Bar.

With a mix of apartment buildings, warehouses, and converted artists lofts, East Williamsburg is part gritty industrial area and part rising creative quarter. Often mis-identified as Bushwick, and sometimes colloquially referred to as Morgantown or Robertasville, East Williamsburg is quickly developing an identity of its own. With plenty of street art, hidden away DIY spaces, historic buildings, tech enterprises, and trendy new shops, East Williamsburg is a place of constant flux, and a happy home for many a self-made creative minds.

Sonia & Francois

AFI REALTY and PROPERTY MANAGEMENT | Corporate Furnished Apartments 

**30 Days Minimum and UP**


AFI Property Management provides high-end furnished and serviced apartments for rent on the Upper East Side of New York. Available for stays of one month or longer, our 1-bedroom studios, 1-bedroom suites and 2-bedroom suites feature an array of amenities, offering guests modern luxury, convenience, and a unique living experience. AFI Property Management designs its own residences, aiming for a vibrant, sophisticated aesthetic and incorporating all the comforts of home. All of our services are performed in-house, allowing us to provide personal, efficient and attentive care to our tenants throughout their stay. 

Property Locations:
Our two pre-war, walk-up apartment buildings are situated on the same city block, at the heart of the Upper East Side neighborhood. Surrounded by some of New York’s best dining, shopping, specialty food stores, schools, and museums, our properties are an ideal place to live like a New Yorker and enjoy what the city has to offer. With convenient proximity to the subway and easy access to public transportation, tenants will be able to make the most out of their time in New York. 

Benefits of staying in one of our apartments:
- Stylish, modern spaces that are move-in ready and equipped with convenient amenities
- Prime Manhattan location, near subway station and bus stops
- On-site management office
- Multilingual management team 
- Key-less electronic entry system allows for effortless, 24-hour check-in
- Kitchen & bath welcome kit provided  
- Exclusive neighborhood guide filled with our hand-picked local favorites

Dance clubs, happening bars and music halls liven up the nightlife scene."

I'm a published poet, travel writer and adjunct professor based in NYC. My husband and I travel a lot and we love to have interesting people stay in our place while we're away.

neighborhood_overview:
Williamsburg is one of Brooklyn's most popular and exciting neighborhoods, straddling old and new. Yet some things in this hipster-hood remain timeless.

You can explore the lively arts, music, and boutique scene here, compose your great American novel on your laptop in numerous cafes, dine in some very good restaurants, and soak up the creative energy and young vibe. A mecca for young creatives since the early aughts, Williamsburg is in the same cosmos as hip East Berlin.

Interestingly, the hip Williamsburg scene plays out against a backdrop of old industrial buildings, modest attached homes (though punctuated by increasing numbers of expensive waterfront high-rises), and a long-standing residential community of Hasidim. Williamsburg is a mish-mash of cultures and vistas, a place that's perhaps not as beautiful as, say, the campus of Brooklyn College, nor as uniform as landmarked brownstone Brooklyn.

neighborhood_overview:
The Upper East Side (UES) is an affluent, storied neighborhood that runs most of the length of Central Park and extends from the park's boundaries to the East River.

This is a culturally rich neighborhood, with the infamous "museum mile" including the famous Metropolitan Museum of Art, the Guggenheim , The Frick, Neue Galerie, Cooper Hewitt Design Museum and the Jewish Museum.

There are a wide range of dining options, ranging from low key diners to some of the best restaurants in Manhattan. Along Madison are plenty of luxury retail shops and further east, an array of casual shops and boutiques.

The true gem of UES is the iconic 840 acre Central Park with miles of walking and running paths, an ice rink in winter, concerts in summer, the Central Park Zoo, woodlands and ponds, a public pool, restaurants, and plenty of green space to play Frisbee or just lay in the sun. neighborhood_overview:
The Upper East Side is one of the most affluent neighborhoods in New York City, known for its luxury high-rise buildings, exclusive shops, and prestigious cultural institutions. The location of this apartment on 75th Street and 2nd-3rd Avenue puts it in the heart of this neighborhood.

The area is home to many famous museums, such as the Metropolitan Museum of Art and the Guggenheim, as well as other cultural institutions like the Whitney Museum of American Art and the Jewish Museum. The neighborhood is also home to many high-end shops and designer boutiques, such as Louis Vuitton, Gucci, and Chanel.

The area also boasts many excellent restaurants, cafes, and bars, catering to a variety of tastes and budgets. Some of the most popular include Cafe Boulud, Sushi Nakazawa, and the Carlyle Hotel's Bemelmans Bar.

The Local Stay, founded in 2008 and offers hundreds of short-term and long-term rental properties in Amsterdam, Barcelona, Buenos Aires, London, New York, New-Jersey, Paris, Rome, Tel Aviv and more. With options for everyone, The Local Stay provides personalized service so that every traveler can stay like a local.

host_about:
Dear Airbnb guests!

Thanks for checking my profile. I manage furnished monthly rentals and co-living spaces in Manhattan, Queens, and Brooklyn with my team members. I have been managing furnished apartments for a decade and have had more than 5,600 guests from 90 countries so far. Please feel free to ask me any questions or requests!

*I can speak Japanese as well! Please feel free to contact me in Japanese.

Who we are: Our Principles

1) Growing Our Alumni Community:
We don’t require any extra/hidden fees to maximize our profits. Instead, our focus is on growing our alumni community. We believe that our services and fair pricing speak for themselves among our guests. Our alumni posted 700+ reviews from 2019 to 2021. What’s more, 80% of the reviews gave us five stars and 97% awarded more than four stars. Our alumni community spans the globe with 87 unique nationalities, and it has been expanding. We look forward to serving all our new guests: our alumni of tomorrow.
‍

‍2) Transparency. One All-Inclusive Price. That’s What We’re About:
There’s no math required. The price for our one-month minimum stay is simple and fair, no matter how long you stay with us. Our one-month price is already competitive (averaging $1,200 to $2,200, with 80% of our 150 rooms under $1,900 per month), compared to others’ discounted prices for three- to six-month stays. In 2020, 50%+ of our customers extended their original stay by a few months. There’s really no substitute for all-inclusive furnished rentals and a co-living environment, with a furnished private room, that’s ready for you on day one.
‍

‍3) Increasing Value for the Local Property Industry:
We provide co-living communities for our guests by helping property owners draw more value from under-managed residential properties. We care about our customer community, of course, but we’re also excited about uniting property owners, vendors, and our team on one digital platform.
‍

‍4) Privacy Is the Priority:
There are no required social events. Our priority is providing privacy, a quiet environment, and security for all our guests. Our team will take care of cleaning the common spaces every week, so that our kitchen/dining areas are always comfortable. But if you want to expand your network or social circle, our office at WeWork offers you day/after-work communities. We just moved our headquarters to the newest WeWork offices in Long Island City, which is easily accessible by all subway lines.


‍5) 10 Years Perfecting the Co-Living Mindset:
Our founder started this business in his apartment after he couldn’t find appropriately priced accommodation for his first three months in New York. But our whole team has experienced co-living firsthand, so we understand what the customer feels and will need next. “We live and breathe co-living: first as roommates, and now serving our co-living guests.”
‍

‍6) A Sustainable Business Model in the Sharing Economy:
We won’t invest in luxury buildings like hotels or event spaces. We rent existing empty apartments and townhouses from the owners, put IKEA-type furniture in, and list the clean rooms on multiple digital platforms. We grow by our operational profit base, which comes from guests being charged fair prices and the revenue owners receive. However, what drives our growth is not the number of rooms, but our deep understanding of how to care for guests and rooms 24/7, and the intangible value within them.
‍

‍7) Our Vision - Making Dreams Come True:
CrossOver’s goal is to help our guests achieve their goals and dreams by providing the most affordable and flexible housing environment available. But it doesn’t stop here. Our guests’ dreams are expanding to a variety of locations around the globe, and CrossOver will be right there with them—powering the dreams of residents, landlords, and our staff in the wider world.

The neighborhood of East 78th St is located in the Upper East Side of Manhattan, New York City. It is considered a prime and upscale neighborhood known for its beautiful pre-war buildings, tree-lined streets, and proximity to some of the city's most notable landmarks and attractions. The area is home to many of the city's most prestigious museums, such as the Metropolitan Museum of Art, the Frick Collection, and the Whitney Museum of American Art.

East 78th St is also known for its high-end shopping and dining options. The neighborhood is home to many designer boutiques, luxury retailers, and high-end department stores such as Bergdorf Goodman and Saks Fifth Avenue. The area also has a diverse array of restaurants and bars, ranging from casual to fine dining options.

neighborhood_overview: The elegant, chic and sophisticated Upper East Side is one of Manhattan’s most coveted neighborhoods. Home to nine of New York City’s finest museums, including the Met and the Guggenheim, it’s widely considered the cultural capital of Manhattan. Known for its tranquil atmosphere, the UES also provides some much-needed peace and quiet in the city that never sleeps. Stroll down the famed Park Avenue, Madison Avenue or Lexington Avenue and ogle at the world-class shopping, extravagant real estate and fine dining restaurants. With Central Park bordering the neighborhood to the west, there’s always somewhere to recharge and get some fresh air. Inside the park, be sure to visit popular destinations like the Central Park Zoo, The Mall and Literary Walk, the Loeb Boathouse and the Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis Reservoir. For a less crowded recreational experience, visit several other small parks that permeate the neighborhood. The Upper East Side’s restaurant scene is incredibly diverse. Whatever

description:
This lovingly restored, vintage literary New York apartment is owned by a local writer/photographer. Built in 1910, this sun-drenched space boasts original wood-flooring throughout, tin ceilings and mid-century furniture.

Located on a quiet, tree-lined block in East Williamsburg, the apartment is in the heart of the action, steps to the subway station, and walking distance to a plethora of wonderful cafes, restaurants, and a beloved Italian-American pastry shop.

A true Brooklyn experience!
neighborhood_overview:
We’ve lovingly restored our classic Brooklyn apartment, and we hope you love your immersion in old New York as much as we do.

You’ve chosen quite a street: down the block is the library from A Tree Grows in Brooklyn, just next door is a beloved Italian pasticceria from the Donnie Brasco days (and the gelato is as good as the cannolis).

And of course you’ve found the best of new Brooklyn as well. You’ll want to get out and explore the wonders of Northside Williamsburg (Bedford Avenue area) and Greenpoint (don’t miss Franklin Avenue), but this hyperlocal guide will get your started. All this and much more is right around the corner!

neighborhood_overview:
Williamsburg is one of Brooklyn's most popular and exciting neighborhoods straddled with old and new. In the last ten years, Williamsburg has evolved from a mostly industrial warehouse neighborhood into an enclave of vintage boutiques, foodie eats, rooftop bars, electronic music venues, and Michelin restaurants. You can explore the lively arts, music, and the boutique scene here, chill in numerous cafes, dine in exceptional restaurants — and soak up the creative energy and unique vibe. People flock to the waterfront for flea marks and giant food bazaars during the summer. Brunch and bike away the day and lounge and drink away the night in this infinitely hip warehouse-turned-loft Brooklyn neighborhood.

The Local Stay, founded in 2008 and offers hundreds of short-term and long-term rental properties in Amsterdam, Barcelona, Buenos Aires, London, New York, New-Jersey, Paris, Rome, Tel Aviv and more. And, since each property owner is personally vetted by The Local Stay team, travelers can rest assured that their stays will be safe and secure. Better vetting means that travelers get the most exclusive apartments in the most central locations, while greater involvement by The Local Stay means that property owners can list it and leave it as we handle communication with renters

name: *PRIME Bedford Ave * Peaceful & Chic +private yard
description:
Welcome to your home away from home in trendy Williamsburg, Brooklyn!

Comfortable and private renovated one-bedroom apt with everything you need, including a brand new king-sized bed! Premium linens and towels for a hotel-like feel, with all the extras of home. Click my profile pic for my num
neighborhood_overview: The apartment is a perfect place to stay if you'd like to enjoy being close to everything but still be able to sleep soundly at night, away from the noise of the city. Though it’s become more refined in recent years, Williamsburg still has a hip lively vibe-with plenty of indie music performances, gallery shows, and shops run by local artisans. Distilleries and wineries show off the neighborhood’s flair for locally made spirits, while Smorgasburg packs in creative food vendors along the riverfront on summer Saturdays. Williamsburg is one of the City’s most exciting nightlife neighborhoods too, with many of NYC’s trendiest restaurants and clubs. With a walk score of 99 everything you might need is within a short walk. Be sure to check out my 'guidebook' section for a great list of places to go!

neighborhood_overview:
Williamsburg, one of Brooklyn's most popular and exciting neighborhoods, straddles old and new. Yet some things in this hipster-hood remain timeless. You can explore the lively arts, music, and boutique scene here, compose your great American novel on your laptop in numerous cafes, dine in some very good restaurants, and soak up the youthful and creative energy.

The hip Williamsburg scene plays out against a backdrop of old industrial buildings, modest attached homes (though punctuated by increasing numbers of expensive waterfront high-rises), and a long-standing residential Jewish community. If there's one neighborhood that's indicative of the "new Brooklyn," it's Williamsburg. Because even if you've lived in Brooklyn for 1,000 years, Williamsburg can sometimes seem like foreign terrain.

neighborhood_overview:
Laid-back Astoria is a multicultural neighborhood known for its Greek tavernas and cafes. The area is home to a variety of traditional ethnic eateries and trendy spots. It's close proximity to Manhattan and LaGuardia airport make it a convenient stay for those who are in-town on business or tourism alike.
Astoria was recently voted as the best NYC neighborhood by Forbes and the 8th coolest in the world by CNN.
Citifield - Home of the Mets & The US Open Tennis are 10 minutes by car.
Astoria Park, well known for featuring a beautiful pool, is the largest and oldest park in all of NYC. Astoria Park boasts a full size running track, tennis courts, picnic area, basketball courts & playgrounds. All with spectacular views of the Manhattan skyline over the East River.
Close walk to Grocery Store (1 block), abundant restaurants and delis nearby
Nearest hospital is Mt Sinai, three blocks away
Very Safe!!

neighborhood_overview: Astoria is the neighborhood in northwestern Queens (pop. approx. 225,000), constituting the part of Long Island City north of Broadway, east of the East River, west of roughly 51st Street and south of the Long Island Sound. There may be as many geographic descriptions of Astoria as there are residents. It was developed from 1839 by Stephen A. Halsey, a fur merchant who petitioned the state legislature to name it for the prominent fur trader John Jacob Astor, in an unsuccessful effort to have Astor become a financial patron of the area. During the 1840s and 1850s it grew slowly inland from the ferry landing at the foot of Astoria Boulevard (where an early settlement was known as Hallett's Cove). Wealthy New Yorkers built mansions on 12th and 14th streets and on 27th Avenue. The German United Cabinet Workers brought four farms in 1869 between 35th and 50th streets and developed a German town. neighborhood_overview:
Astoria is a thriving neighborhood in Queens teeming with a diversity of people, shops, and restaurants. It was named after John Astor, the nation’s first multi-millionaire.

Home to Little Egypt and the largest Greek community outside of Greece, excellent Middle Eastern and Greek food abounds. But Astoria also boasts so much more food—Colombian, Czech, Thai, Italian, Indian, Peruvian, and a centuries-old beer garden (The Bohemian Hall).

Steinway Piano Company was born in Astoria in 1870 and is still here! Take a tour and see how these world-famous pianos are made.

Noguchi Museum is in Astoria. Love modern art and design? Don’t miss visiting.

name: 323-2 Spacious 2BR Williamsburg
description: This remarkable 2-bedroom, 1-bathroom property on Graham Avenue in Williamsburg, Brooklyn, presents a truly exceptional opportunity that rarely comes along. It's more than just a place to stay; it's a haven for relaxation and rejuvenation, whether your day is filled with work or play. This unit is located in the beautifully safe area of Williamsburg, and it is equipped with everything you could need during your stay.
neighborhood_overview:
Williamsburg is a neighborhood located in northern Brooklyn, known for its industrial heritage and robust artistic community. It's bordered by Greenpoint to the north; Bedford–Stuyvesant to the south; Bushwick and East Williamsburg to the east; and the East River to the west.

Historically, Williamsburg was an industrial district and a bustling hub for working-class immigrants. However, it has transformed into a vibrant neighborhood adorned with street art, trendy boutiques, and eclectic eateries. It's also become a beacon of Brooklyn creativity, attracting an overflow of artists from downtown Manhattan.

In the 21st century, Williamsburg has emerged as a pop-culture darling, defining NYC trends. It's become popular with young professionals due to its vibrant social activities and easy commute to Manhattan. Williamsburg combines a rich history with a trendy, hip lifestyle, making it a popular choice for those seeking a vibrant Brooklyn experience.

neighborhood_overview:
The Upper East Side is one of the most desirable neighborhoods in New York City, known for its upscale residential buildings, high-end shopping, and iconic cultural institutions. The area is home to a number of renowned museums such as the Metropolitan Museum of Art, the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum, and the Neue Galerie New York. The Upper East Side is also a shopper's paradise, with designer boutiques and luxury brands lining Madison Avenue and Fifth Avenue.

Foodies will also enjoy the diverse culinary offerings in the area, with a variety of restaurants and cafes serving up everything from classic New York bagels to Michelin-starred cuisine. The Upper East Side also boasts numerous parks and green spaces, including Central Park, which is just a walk away from the apartment.

Overall, the Upper East Side is a vibrant and dynamic neighborhood, offering residents and visitors alike a unique blend of cultural, artistic, and culinary experiences.

neighborhood_overview:
East 66th Street in New York City, you have access to several public transportation options:

Subway:
• 68th Street–Hunter College Station: Located at East 68th Street and Lexington Avenue, this station serves the 6 train, providing service along the Lexington Avenue Line.

Bus Services:
• M66 Bus: This crosstown route runs along 65th and 66th Streets, connecting the Upper East Side to the Upper West Side.
• M15 and M15 Select Bus Service (SBS): Operating on First Avenue (northbound) and Second Avenue (southbound), these buses provide service between East Harlem and Lower Manhattan.
• M101, M102, and M103 Buses: These routes run along Third Avenue (northbound) and Lexington Avenue (southbound), offering service between Upper Manhattan and the East Village or City Hall.

These options offer convenient access to various parts of Manhattan from your location.

neighborhood_overview:
With so much to see and do right at your doorstep, the possibilities are endless. Take a leisurely stroll to the Central Park, where you can marvel at breathtaking views of the city skyline. Or, venture further afield and discover hidden gems that only the locals know about. From cultural landmarks to outdoor adventures, there's something for everyone to enjoy.

To many New Yorkers, the Upper East Side connotes old money and high society. Alongside Central Park, between 5th and Lexington avenues, up to East 96th Street, the trappings of wealth are everywhere apparent: posh buildings, Madison Avenue's flagship boutiques, and doormen in braided livery. It’s also a key destination for visitors, because some of the most fantastic museums in the country are here.

neighborhood_overview:
There are SO many reasons why everyone wants to live in Williamsburg. You're one stop away from Manhattan on the nearby L or JMZ trains, or if you're feeling adventurous, you can hop on a CitiBike or walk across the iconic Williamsburg Bridge.

That being said, you'll probably find it hard to leave Williamsburg, since it has everything you could ever want right outside your door. Enjoy a walk by the water at Domino Park or soak up some sun while dog watching at McCarren Park. Wander through the countless shops on and around Bedford Avenue. Grab a bite or a drink at any of the innumerable bars and restaurants in the area. If nightlife is your thing, Williamsburg has plenty of great spots to dance your way through the evening. In the unlikely event that you run out of things to do in Williamsburg, Greenpoint (our friendly neighbor to the north) is an easy walk and boasts its own extensive roster of shops, bars, restaurants, clubs and more.
